2005|p=154}}\n|-\n|\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/\u0252\u02d0/}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[\u0252\u02d0]}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[\u0252\u031d\u02d0]}}\n| ''m'''or'''se''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;\u0254\u02d0r&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| ''t'''\u00e5r'''ne''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;\u0254\u02d0&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/\u0254\u02d0/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0254\u031d\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0254\u033d\u02d0]}}\n| ''m'''\u00e5'''le''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;\u0259&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/\u0259/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0259]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0259]}}\n| ''hopp'''e'''''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;\u0259r&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| rowspan=\"3\" | {{IPA|/\u0250/}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" | {{IPA|[\u0250]}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" | {{IPA|[\u0252\u033d]}}\n| ''fatt'''er'''''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;r\u0259&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| ''tu'''re'''''\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: left;\" | After long vowels.{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|pp=72, 81}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;r\u0259r&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| ''tu'''rer'''''\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;j\u0259&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/j\u0259/}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[\u026a]}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[\u026a]}}\n| ''ve'''je'''''\n| rowspan=\"11\" style=\"text-align: left;\" | See {{section link||Schwa-assimilation}}.\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;\u0261\u0259&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| ''ja'''ge'''''\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;v\u0259&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/v\u0259/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u028a]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u028a]}}\n| ''ha'''ve'''''\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;\u0259d&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/\u0259\u00f0/}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[\u00f0\u0329]}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[\u00f0\u0329\u02d5\u02d7\u02e0]}}\n| ''m\u00e5n'''ed'''''\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;d\u0259&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/\u00f0\u0259/}}\n| ''ba'''de'''''\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;\u0259l&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/\u0259l/}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[l\u0329]}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[l\u0329]}}\n| ''gamm'''el'''''\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;l\u0259&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/l\u0259/}}\n| ''ta'''le'''''\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;n\u0259&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/n\u0259/}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[n\u0329]}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[n\u0329]}}\n| ''h\u00e5'''ne'''''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | {{IPA|&#124;\u0259n&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| rowspan=\"3\" | {{IPA|/\u0259n/}}\n| ''hest'''en'''''\n|-\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|[m\u0329]}}\n| {{IPA|[m\u0329]}}\n| ''hopp'''en'''''\n|-\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|[\u014b\u030d]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u014b\u030d]}}\n| ''pakk'''en'''''\n|}\n\nThe three way distinction in front rounded vowels {{IPA|/y \u00f8 \u0153/}} is upheld only before nasals, e.g. {{IPA|/syns s\u00f8n\u02c0s s\u0153ns/}} ''synes, synds, s\u00f8ns'' ('seems', 'sin's', 'son's'). Furthermore, there are only three words where {{IPA|/y/}} occurs before a nasal in a stressed syllable: ''synes, brynje, hymne'' ('seems, armor, hymn').{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=51}}{{failed verification|date=February 2017}}<!--Basb\u00f8ll gives some of these examples on that page, but doesn't make any of these claims.-->\n\n{{IPA|/a/}} and {{IPA|/a\u02d0/}} on one hand and {{IPA|/\u0251/}} and {{IPA|/\u0251\u02d0/}} on the other are largely in complementary distribution. However, a two-phoneme interpretation can be justified with reference to the unexpected vowel quality in words like ''andre'' {{IPA|/\u02c8andr\u0250/}} 'others' or ''anderledes'' {{IPA|/\u02c8an\u0250\u02ccle\u02d0\u00f0\u0259s/}} 'different', and an increasing number of loanwords.{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|pp=50\u20131}}\n\nThe vowel system is unstable, and according to at least one study,{{sfnp|Ejstrup|Hansen|2004}} the contemporary spoken language might be experiencing a merger of several of these vowels. The following vowel pairs may be merged by some speakers, leading in some cases to phonemic mergers:\n* {{IPA|[\u028a]}} with {{IPA|[o]}}, leading to a variable merger of {{IPA|/v\u0259/}} and {{IPA|/o/}} (the former can be {{IPA|[w\u0259]}} or {{IPA|[w\u028a]}} instead, in which case no merger takes place).{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=58}}\n* {{IPA|[e\u031d]}} with {{IPA|[e]}}, which is phonemic if the allophones appearing in {{IPA|/r/}}-contexts are analyzed as {{IPA|/a/}} and {{IPA|/\u0251/}}.{{sfnp|Ejstrup|Hansen|2004}}\n* {{IPA|[e\u031d\u02d0]}} with {{IPA|[e\u02d0]}}, which is phonemic if the allophones appearing in {{IPA|/r/}}-contexts are analyzed as {{IPA|/a\u02d0/}} and {{IPA|/\u0251\u02d0/}}.{{sfnp|Ejstrup|Hansen|2004}}\n* {{IPA|/\u025b\u02d0/}} with {{IPA|/a\u02d0/}}{{sfnp|Ejstrup|Hansen|2004}}\n* {{IPA|[\u00f8]}} with {{IPA|[\u0153\u031d]}}, leading to phonemization of the {{IPA|[\u0153]}} allophone.{{sfnp|Ejstrup|Hansen|2004}}\n* {{IPA|[\u00f8\u02d0]}} with {{IPA|[\u0153\u031d\u02d0]}}.{{sfnp|Ejstrup|Hansen|2004}}\n* {{IPA|[o]}} with {{IPA|[\u0254\u031d]}}, so that {{IPA|/o/}} has only one allophone.{{sfnp|Ejstrup|Hansen|2004}}\n* {{IPA|/o\u02d0/}} with {{IPA|/\u0254\u02d0/}}{{sfnp|Ejstrup|Hansen|2004}}\n* {{IPA|/\u0250/}} with {{IPA|/\u028c/}}{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=58}}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Schwa-assimilation==\nIn addition to {{IPA|/\u0250/}}, which stems from the fusion of {{IPA|{{!}}\u0259r{{!}}}}, {{IPA|{{!}}r\u0259{{!}}}}, or {{IPA|{{!}}r\u0259r{{!}}}}, {{IPA|/\u0259/}} assimilates to adjacent [[sonorant]]s in a variety of ways:{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|pp=186\u20137}}\n\n* {{IPA|/\u0259/}} assimilates to preceding long vowels: {{IPA|/\u02c8di\u02d0\u0259/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8ti\u02d0i]}} ''die'' 'nurse', {{IPA|/\u02c8du\u02d0\u0259/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8tu\u02d0u]}} ''due'' 'pigeon'.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=186}}\n* {{IPA|/j\u0259/}} after a long vowel other than {{IPA|/i\u02d0, y\u02d0/}} and {{IPA|/v\u0259/}} after a long vowel other than {{IPA|/u\u02d0/}} become monophthongs {{IPA|[\u026a, \u028a]}}: {{IPA|/\u02c8l\u025b\u02d0j\u0259/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8le\u02d0\u026a]}} ''l\u00e6ge'' 'doctor', {{IPA|/\u02c8l\u0254\u02d0v\u0259/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8l\u0254\u031d\u02d0\u028a]}} ''l\u00e5ge'' 'gate'.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|pp=186\u20137}} In innovative varieties, the vowels may become shorter: {{IPA|[\u02c8lej\u026a], [\u02c8l\u0254\u031dw\u028a]}}.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=269}}\n* A sonorant consonant ({{IPA|/\u00f0, l, m, n, \u014b/}}) and {{IPA|/\u0259/}}, in either order, become a [[syllabic consonant]] {{IPA|[\u00f0\u0329, l\u0329, m\u0329, n\u0329, \u014b\u030d]}}.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|pp=301\u20132}}\n** It is longer after a short vowel than after a long one: {{IPA|/\u02c8ba\u02d0\u00f0\u0259/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8p\u00e6\u02d0\u00f0\u0329]}} ''bade'' 'bathe', {{IPA|/\u02c8hu\u02d0l\u0259/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8hu\u02d0l\u0329]}} ''hule'' 'cave', {{IPA|/\u02c8sbi\u00f0\u0259/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8spi\u00f0\u00f0\u0329]}} ''spidde'' 'spear', {{IPA|/\u02c8kul\u0259/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8k\u02b0ull\u0329]}} ''kulde'' 'cold'.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=187}}\n** When {{IPA|/\u0259/}} is placed between two sonorant consonants, the second becomes syllabic: {{IPA|/\u02c8sa\u00f0\u0259l/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8s\u00e6\u00f0l\u0329]}} ''saddel'' 'saddle', {{IPA|/\u02c8hyl\u0259\u00f0/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8hyl\u00f0\u0329]}} ''hyldet'' 'praised'.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=187}}\n** The place of a syllabic nasal ({{IPA|/\u0259n/}}) assimilates to that of the preceding consonant: {{IPA|/\u02c8l\u0251b\u0259n/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8l\u0251pm\u0329]}} ''lappen'' 'patches', {{IPA|/\u02c8l\u0251\u0261\u0259n/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8l\u0251k\u014b\u030d]}} ''lakken'' 'varnishes'.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=302}}\n\nIn casual speech, {{IPA|/\u0259/}} may also be elided after an [[obstruent]]. If that occurs after a long vowel, the syllable with the elided {{IPA|/\u0259/}} may be retained by lengthening the vowel preceding the consonant: {{IPA|/\u02c8h\u0254\u02d0b\u0259/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8h\u0254\u031d\u02d0(\u0254\u031d)p]}} ''h\u00e5be'' 'hope'.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=187}}\n\n==Prosody==\n\n===Stress===\nUnlike the neighboring Mainland Scandinavian languages Swedish and Norwegian, the prosody of Danish does not have phonemic pitch. [[stress (linguistics)|Stress]] is phonemic and distinguishes words like ''billigst'' {{IPA|[\u02c8pilist]}} ('cheapest') and ''bilist'' {{IPA|[pi\u02c8list]}} ('car driver'). In syntactic phrases, verbs lose their stress (and st\u00f8d, if any) with an [[Object (grammar)|object]] without a definite or indefinite [[Article (grammar)|article]]: e.g. ''\u02c8Jens \u02c8spiser et \u02c8br\u00f8d'' {{IPA|[\u02c8jens \u02c8spi\u02c0s\u0250 e\u031dt \u02c8p\u0281\u0153\u031d\u00f0\u02c0]}} ('Jens eats a loaf') ~ ''\u02c8Jens spiser \u02c8br\u00f8d'' {{IPA|[\u02c8jens spis\u0250 \u02c8p\u0281\u0153\u031d\u00f0\u02c0]}} ('Jens eats bread'). In names, only the surname is stressed, e.g. {{IPA|[joh\u00e6n\u0329lui\u02d0s\u0259 \u02c8h\u0251j\u02ccp\u025b\u031d\u0250\u032f\u02c0]}} ''[[Johanne Luise Heiberg]]''.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|1998|p=104}}\n\n===St\u00f8d===\n{{main|St\u00f8d}}\nIn a number of words with stress on the final syllable, long vowels and sonorants may exhibit a prosodic feature called ''st\u00f8d'' ('thrust').{{sfnp|Haberland|1994|p=318}} Acoustically, vowels with st\u00f8d tend to be a little shorter{{sfnp|Haberland|1994|p=318}} and feature [[creaky voice]].{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=83}} Historically, this feature operated as a redundant aspect of stress on monosyllabic words that had either a long vowel or final voiced consonant. Since the creation of new monosyllabic words, this association with monosyllables is no longer as strong. Some other tendencies include:\n*Polysyllabic words with the nominal definite suffix ''-et'' may exhibit st\u00f8d{{sfnp|Haberland|1994|p=318}}\n*Polysyllabic loanwords with final stress on either a long vowel or a vowel with a final sonorant typically feature st\u00f8d{{sfnp|Haberland|1994|p=318}}\n\nDiphthongs with an underlying long vowel always have st\u00f8d.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=294}}\n\n== Text sample ==\nThe sample text is an indistinct reading of the first sentence of [[The North Wind and the Sun]].\n\n===Orthographic version===\nNordenvinden og solen kom engang i strid om, hvem af dem der var den st\u00e6rkeste.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|1998|p=104}}\n\n===Broad phonetic transcription===\n{{IPA|[\u02c8no\u0250\u032f\u0250n\u02ccve\u031dn\u02c0n\u0329 \u028c \u02c8so\u02c0l\u0329n k\u02b0\u028cm e\u031d\u014b\u02c8k\u0251\u014b\u02c0 i \u02c8st\u0281i\u00f0\u02c0 \u02c8\u028cm\u02c0 \u02c8vem\u02c0 \u02c8\u00e6 pm\u0329 t\u0251 v\u0251 tn\u0329 \u02c8st\u025b\u031d\u0250\u032fk\u0259st\u0259]}}{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|1998|p=104}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{citation\n|last=Abrahams\n|first=Henrik\n|year=1949\n|title=\u00c9tudes phon\u00e9tiques sur les tendances \u00e9volutives des occlusives germaniques\n|publisher=Aarhus University Press\n}}\n* {{citation\n|last=Allan\n|first=Robin\n|last2=Holmes\n|first2=Philip\n|last3=Lundsk\u00e6r-Nielsen\n|first3=Tom\n|year=2011\n|orig-year=First published 2000\n|title=Danish: An Essential Grammar\n|edition=2nd\n|publisher=Routledge\n|place=Abingdon\n|isbn=978-0-203-87800-2\n}}\n* {{citation\n|last=Basb\u00f8ll\n|first=Hans\n|authorlink=Hans Basb\u00f8ll\n|year=2005\n|title=The Phonology of Danish\n|publisher=Oxford University Press\n|place=Oxford\n|isbn=0-203-97876-5\n}}\n* {{citation\n|last1=Brink\n|first1=Lars\n|last2=Lund\n|first2=J\u00f8rn\n|last3=Heger\n|first3=Steffen\n|last4=J\u00f8rgensen\n|first4=J. Normann\n|year=1991\n|title=Den Store Danske Udtaleordbog\n|publisher=Munksgaard\n|isbn=87-16-06649-9\n}}\n* {{citation\n|last1=Ejstrup\n|first1=Michael\n|last2=Hansen\n|first2=Gert Foget\n|year=2004\n|title=Vowels in regional variants of Danish\n|publisher=Department of Linguistics, Stockholm University\n|place=Stockholm\n|url=http://www.ling.su.se/fon/fonetik_2004/ejstrup_hansen_fonetik2004.pdf\n}}\n* {{citation\n|last=Fischer-J\u00f8rgensen\n|first=Eli\n|authorlink=Eli Fischer-J\u00f8rgensen\n|chapter=Om stemtheds assimilation\n|year=1952\n|editor1-last=Bach\n|editor